From 6144a4bb6b1182e635fb88dd737cd11fd71e6189 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 03:26:43 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] darlingserver: run cheap RPCs inline on the main loop (perf
 #2b)

Under a fork/checkin storm (Homebrew `make -j`), profiling (perf #2a, bead
dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.7) showed ~70% of darlingserver CPU was spent in the
main-loop -> worker-pool handoff, NOT in the kernel emulation: per inbound
message the single event loop did _workQueue.push() -> pthread_cond_signal ->
kernel futex_wake to wake a parked worker that did sub-microsecond work and
immediately re-parked. The actual RPC work (callFromMessage 0.66%, doWork
0.51%) was <1% of CPU; the wakeup tax dwarfed it. This is why enabling the
multi-threaded work queue made the server ~32% SLOWER than single-threaded
(live A/B: ST ~3830 checkin/s vs naive MT ~2594/s) -- and why upstream left
DSERVER_SINGLE_THREADED on.

Fix: in the event loop, run the call's microthread INLINE via Thread::doWork()
instead of always pushing it to the pool. doWork() never blocks its caller --
a non-blocking call (the overwhelming majority: checkin, self-traps, port ops,
etc.) runs to completion right there with zero wakeup; a call that blocks
suspends its microthread (setcontext back to the loop) having already arranged
its own resume onto the work queue, so the loop keeps serving and only the
genuinely-blocking minority ever uses a worker. New metrics inline_handled /
queued_to_pool make the split observable.

Live A/B (8-proc tcstorm multistorm, DSERVER_SINGLE_THREADED=OFF):
  ST baseline:      ~3830 checkin/s, p50 16-32us, p95/p99 512us
  naive MT:         ~2594 checkin/s, p50 64us,    p95/p99 512us  (regression)
  inline + MT:    4676-7295 checkin/s, p50 8us,   p95/p99 64us
=> +22%..+90% throughput over ST, ~8x better p99 latency, and 99.998% of RPCs
handled inline (241 of 11.27M went to the pool). Boot + 200x fork/exec/wait
correctness (exit codes, pipelines) verified; server stable across runs.

RED->GREEN regression test committed alongside (tests/server_inline_fastpath.c
+ run-server-inline-fastpath.sh): models the two dispatch strategies over an
identical tiny RPC and gates on context-switches/item -- the per-message
handoff path incurs ~1 ctx-switch/item (RED, fails), the inline path ~0
(GREEN, passes).

Bead: dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.8

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
